description: From Arabic فَلَّاح‎ (fallāḥ, “peasant”), from Classical Syriac ܦܠܚܐ‎ (“worker; peasant”). Attested since 1743.

nouns.description: fellah (plural fellahs or fellahin or fellaheen)

entries.meaning: A peasant, farmer or agricultural laborer in the Middle East and North Africa.
examples: Religion long kept the two races, Arab and Egyptian, apart, and when eventually the Christian fellaḥ in the neighbourhood of Cairo had become Mohammedan, the Mohammedan Arab had become a townsman with a townsman’s sense of superiority over the country bumpkin.

description: Representing an eye dialect pronunciation of fellow.
